1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
 Hello and welcome to Object Oriented Patterns, A Historical Perspective.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,000
 We're going to cover a number of different things in this lecture.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:12,000
 First, we're going to do a bit of a review of object orientation from previous courses.

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:18,000
 Then we're going to take a look at historical perspective across time and a bunch of different programming languages.

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:24,000
 The important part about that is that object orientation is a concept, it's not just a syntax.

6
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:29,000
 And so by looking at different syntaxes, we'll have a better understanding of the underlying concept.

7
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:39,000
 Then what we're going to do is we'll look at how one might have used C to build object oriented support into a language like, say, Python, for example, or C++.

8
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:47,000
 And then we're going to look at building a Python string class in C, a Python list class in C, and then a Python dictionary class in C.

9
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:55,000
 Sort of showing how C is also the foundation of most modern object oriented languages.

10
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:00,000
 So if you take a look at the other courses that I've taught, I have been teaching object oriented.

11
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:05,000
 If you take in my courses, I have been teaching you object orientation for a long time.

12
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:09,000
 One of the things you'll notice is that I just keep coming back to it.

13
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:14,000
 If you look at Python for Everybody Chapter 14, it's about object orientation.

14
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 I claim that Django for Everybody is really a class in object orientation because Django itself is a collection of cooperating objects.

15
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:33,000
 You create Django applications by creating objects that are being sent messages, which is very much a purely object oriented concept.

16
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:38,000
 I cover object oriented JavaScript, particularly because JavaScript is a little bit different.

17
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:43,000
 I cover that in both Django for Everybody and in web applications for everybody.

18
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:53,000
 And so we're going to take a look at all these different syntaxes of object orientation, and then we're going to try to build our own objects.

19
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 But in a non-object oriented language, i.e. C.

20
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
 I am not going to teach you object orientation in this lecture.

21
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:02,000
 I am going to do a very, very brief review.

22
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,000
 On my other lectures, mostly what I wanted you to know was terminology.

23
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,000
 So the most important terminology is a class.

24
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 A class is not an object. It's a template to make objects.

25
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:14,000
 It's like the cookie cutter in the cookie methodology.

26
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:18,000
 An attribute is some data that you can contain in each instance of the class.

27
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:23,000
 And a method is some code like a function that operates within the context of the instance of the class.

28
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:30,000
 The object is a particular instance of the class stamped out from the class when a new instance of the class is requested.

29
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:33,000
 So you have one class that you have many, many instances.

30
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:42,000
 So if you do a user defined class in Python, you see that we have a special keyword class, which is different than def.

31
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:47,000
 And within it, we have attributes and we have methods.

32
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:49,000
 So the methods look like functions.

33
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:58,000
 But in particular, the methods inside of a class always have this first parameter, which by convention we call self.

34
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:02,000
 You could call it literally anything else, but if you did, people would be confused.

35
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 Because the convention is so strong that self is always the first parameter of every method inside of Python.

36
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:15,000
 So in it is the instance and then two parameters.

37
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:24,000
 And then we can look at attributes like self.x and self.y and then assign them in this case to the x and y from the call.

38
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:27,000
 So we have a couple of methods like def dump.

39
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:34,000
 And again, a dump itself is a zero parameter method, but it always has the instance.

40
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:39,000
 And then we look within it, we can say self.x and self.y and look at all the attributes.

41
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:46,000
 And we can use the ID function, which we learned in the last chapter, which is kind of like an address look up function in Python.

42
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:53,000
 And so what we have here is we have a little method called origin, which takes the distance for our point from the origin to our point

43
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:56,000
 and takes the square root of the two sides of the triangle squared.

44
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:05,000
 So if we then get out of the class definition and move into the actual code, we call pt equals .4050.

45
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:07,000
 That is how we call the constructor.

46
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:13,000
 Point is the class name and then the parameters to the constructor are four and five in that example.

47
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 Point.dump, that's the dump method inside a point.

48
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,000
 And you can pass the parameter pt, which is the instance.

49
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 So pt ends up being the instance of this point object.

50
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 But the more common syntax is to not use the class name and the method name and explicitly pass self in.

51
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 But instead in the next line, we see print origin and then pt.origin.

52
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:47,000
 Well, pt.origin is expanded to point.origin and then the first parameter is kind of added on, which is pt, which is the instance.

53
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:53,000
 Now I've got a del parenthesis pt close parenthesis and that is the destructor.

54
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 Now in Python, the destructor would get run automatically at the end of the program.

55
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:01,000
 So in this case, that destructor is a little bit redundant.

56
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:05,000
 So now I want to take a bit of a historical look at object orientation.

57
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:12,000
 So if you've seen any of my other classes, I try to put the programming languages that we're learning in context.

58
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 And these are the common programming languages like Python and PHP and JavaScript.

59
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
 And now we're teaching C.

60
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:33,000
 And so if you look at this, the idea is you can see that the language C has been the inspiration for virtually all of the modern languages that we use today and that I've taught you.

61
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 While the syntax of Python doesn't look like C, Python has been inspired.

62
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 We see things like there's formatted printing that talks directly to the underlying C implementation because C Python, not every Python, but the C Python that we normally use is written in C.

63
00:05:51,000 --> 00:06:01,000
 So C, as we've said many times in this class already, is profoundly influential in the syntactical evolution of procedural programming language.

64
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:16,000
 So we've seen this before. But if we think about object orientation, object orientation, the inspiration and evolution of object orientation really took sort of a different path through a bunch of languages that you may or may not have seen or heard.

65
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:34,000
 So the oldest language on this is Fortran in 1955 and Algal 60. Algal 60, I don't have it marked as like that Algal 60 was inspired by Fortran, but probably the better thing to say was that Algal 60 was created in spite of Fortran.

66
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:44,000
 So Fortran was loved by some and not loved by others. And Algal 60 is more what the computer scientists of the day in 1960 decided.

67
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 So there's a series of languages that were popular in computer science, but not necessarily popular in general purpose programming, like Simula 67, which took a lot of the object oriented ideas from Algal 60.

68
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:08,000
 And Pascal, which is a procedural language, which is another language that I learned in the 70s when I was going to school.

69
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:18,000
 And if you look for, so Algal and Simula were languages that were mostly procedural but had object oriented concepts in them.

70
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:29,000
 I always think of the most object oriented languages as small talk. It's not necessarily the first one, but it feels like it's the one that developed the notion of object orientation the most.

71
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:42,000
 But it really took inspiration from an earlier language, which was Lisp. And so Lisp was an early, early 1960 interpreted language. Lisp was often thought of as the foundations of artificial intelligence.

72
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 Now Scheme in 1975 was a derivative of Lisp, inspired by Lisp, kind of the next generation of Lisp 15 years later. And it had a bunch of object oriented concepts in it as well.

73
00:07:55,000 --> 00:08:09,000
 And so you can kind of see where, where the object oriented notation, the object oriented notions were evolving kind of independently from the preferred syntax.

74
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:24,000
 And then in the 70s, when C came along, it really changed the way we think of syntax. And so it inspired C++, inspired Java, JavaScript, C# and PHP.

75
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:31,000
 But then what happened is each of these things kind of took different inspiration from different object orientation.

76
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:42,000
 So there's really almost an independent inheritance of where the inspiration for the language came from versus where the inspiration for the object oriented pattern.

77
00:08:42,000 --> 00:09:03,000
 And probably the biggest thing that you see is C++, which is early 80s, took its inspiration both from Simula and from C. So it was the hybrid language that tried to take the object oriented notations from Simula and layer them on top of the procedural syntax of C.

78
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:17,000
 Now, another interesting thing here is, is that Python in 1991 was quite aware of C++. And so if you look at PHP, which in 1995 was not at all object oriented, it wasn't object oriented until 2000.

79
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 Python was object oriented in sort of almost 1991, 92, because the computer scientists of the day were quite aware of these kinds of things. And so Python sort of implemented object orientation almost as soon as Python was implemented.

80
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 And so, like I said, Python 1991 implemented object orientation, and I really like the object orientation in Python. PHP implemented non-object oriented in 95, but then added objects in 2000.

81
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:58,000
 Java took a lot of inspiration from C++. Java was trying to be the next C. And so it's got a lot from C. It's got a lot from C++.

82
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:19,000
 And then C# was inspired by C++ and Java. But then JavaScript is kind of like the outlier. JavaScript, even though it came out in 1995 and was very much informed by Java, it took its object oriented pattern more from Scheme, which is a more pure object orientation rather than an object oriented layer.

83
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:37,000
 And so JavaScript, among all of these things that we'll look at, JavaScript is sort of the outlier in terms of its object oriented approach. And if you've taken classes from me in the past, I've mentioned that before, because JavaScript has first class functions and the way you create things, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

84
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:50,000
 So we're going to take a look at some of these object oriented implementations over time. I've already talked about the Python inspiration. I flipped Python in C++ in the early days, because at least Python we kind of know.

85
00:10:50,000 --> 00:11:11,000
 C++ is 1980, Java in '95, JavaScript in '95, PHP in 2000, and then C# in 2001.

